WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.050 --> 00:00:02.341
FEMALE SPEAKER: Please welcome
Professor Jared Diamond.

00:00:02.341 --> 00:00:06.090
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:06.090 --> 00:00:08.560
JARED DIAMOND: It's a
pleasure to be with you today,

00:00:08.560 --> 00:00:15.930
even though my 26-year-old twin
sons will laugh very hard when

00:00:15.930 --> 00:00:18.540
they hear where I've
been today, because they

00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:23.250
know my total
technological incompetence.

00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:26.980
And so I feel obliged to
warn you at the outset

00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:30.100
that I am here under
false pretenses

00:00:30.100 --> 00:00:33.610
if you think that I'm
capable of communicating

00:00:33.610 --> 00:00:36.170
with you about
technological matters.

00:00:36.170 --> 00:00:38.130
But I can talk about books.

00:00:38.130 --> 00:00:40.960
And the occasion for
my being in New York

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:45.710
is the release of
a young persons

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:48.700
edition for the first
time of one of my books.

00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:53.050
It's the first of my books, "The
Third Chimpanzee," now being

00:00:53.050 --> 00:00:57.490
released in a version
aimed at high school

00:00:57.490 --> 00:01:01.160
students and middle
school students.

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:04.730
The background to
my writing this book

00:01:04.730 --> 00:01:09.900
and my writing subsequent
books was somewhat indirect.

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:13.480
This book, the first of my
books for a broad public,

00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:16.060
was published when
I was 55 years old,

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:19.520
so this came relatively
late in life.

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:27.030
I got my PhD in the specialty
of studying sodium transport

00:01:27.030 --> 00:01:28.810
in the gall bladder.

00:01:28.810 --> 00:01:31.280
I trained as a
laboratory physiologist.

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:34.210
And I was hired by
UCLA medical school

00:01:34.210 --> 00:01:39.270
in 1966 to teach medical
students about the physiology

00:01:39.270 --> 00:01:43.470
of gall bladders, intestines,
kidneys, and related organs.

00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:48.210
This book clearly is not in the
area of my research specialty.

00:01:48.210 --> 00:01:52.070
At the same time, I had become
a bird watcher, an amateur bird

00:01:52.070 --> 00:01:55.490
watcher, when I
was seven years old

00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:59.760
and continued bird watching
throughout high school,

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:00.860
college.

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:04.370
After I got my PhD, I was
interested in gall bladder

00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:07.200
research and the challenges
of laboratory physiology.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:11.660
But it dawned on me
with growing horror

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:14.690
that I was expected to
devote the rest of my life

00:02:14.690 --> 00:02:19.970
to writing papers on gall
bladders for the world's four

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:22.230
other gallbladder experts.

00:02:22.230 --> 00:02:26.060
That seemed confining.

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:30.290
There are many other
interesting things in the world.

00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:34.700
In the course of the 1980s,
I began writing articles

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:38.100
about subjects other than
birds and gall bladders

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:44.260
for the weekly journals,
first "Nature" and "Science."

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:46.470
And that led to my
writing articles

00:02:46.470 --> 00:02:49.660
for so-called popular
science magazines, "Discover"

00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:52.420
and "Natural History Magazine."

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:56.040
But I had still not
thought of writing a book.

00:02:56.040 --> 00:03:00.410
The triggering event
for me was the birth

00:03:00.410 --> 00:03:06.420
of my wife's and my
twin sons in 1987,

00:03:06.420 --> 00:03:08.770
when I was nearly 50 years old.

00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:11.630
Until then, I had read
the sorts of things

00:03:11.630 --> 00:03:14.820
that I'm sure that all of you
read about the things that

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:20.730
may happen by such and
such a year if we continue

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:25.200
on our present course of
exploiting world resources.

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:30.600
One reads that by 2050, the
world's tropical rainforests

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:32.690
will essentially
all be destroyed

00:03:32.690 --> 00:03:35.650
outside of the Amazon basin
and perhaps parts of the Congo

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:36.590
basin.

00:03:36.590 --> 00:03:39.170
One reads that the
world's fisheries

00:03:39.170 --> 00:03:42.410
will have largely
collapsed by 2040.

00:03:42.410 --> 00:03:44.400
One reads that
global warming will

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:47.400
have reached such and
such temperature by 2060.

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:50.390
And until the birth
of my sons, whenever

00:03:50.390 --> 00:03:52.050
people talked about
what would happen

00:03:52.050 --> 00:03:57.770
in 2050, end of the rainforest,
because I was born in 1937,

00:03:57.770 --> 00:03:59.740
I'm not going to
be around in 2050.

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:03.680
2050 was an arbitrary
unreal date.

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:06.770
It might have been 2567.

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:10.660
I can't get very excited about
things will happen in 2567.

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:13.240
And I also could not
get excited about things

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:15.720
projected happen in 2050.

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:18.130
Then our sons were born.

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:25.070
And I realized with a jolt that
2050 is not an imaginary year

00:04:25.070 --> 00:04:26.600
far off in the future.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:30.850
My sons will be 63
years old in 2050 .

00:04:30.850 --> 00:04:34.280
They will be at the
peak of their lives,

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:36.500
even short of the
peak of their lives.

00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:38.230
They'll have decades
ahead of them.

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:42.550
So 2050 is not an
imaginary date.

00:04:42.550 --> 00:04:46.330
It's instead a very real
date for my children.

00:04:46.330 --> 00:04:52.290
And yet my wife and I
when our kids were born

00:04:52.290 --> 00:04:54.040
began doing the
things that parents

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:59.530
do when children are born,
namely we drew up wills.

00:04:59.530 --> 00:05:02.360
We did estate planning.

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:04.790
We bought life insurance.

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:08.270
And I realized that
there was a disconnect.

00:05:08.270 --> 00:05:13.300
What on earth are we
doing drawing up wills

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:16.720
and buying life insurance
and forming a trust

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:21.110
if the world in which my
kids will find themselves

00:05:21.110 --> 00:05:24.820
in the year 2050 is a
world not worth living in,

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:27.030
if we've messed up the world?

00:05:27.030 --> 00:05:31.640
It did not make sense for us
to be devoting this effort

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:34.620
to these practical
concerns of life insurance

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:40.280
if I was not also dealing with
the big problems of the world

00:05:40.280 --> 00:05:43.150
that might make
the world of 2050

00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:46.570
a world not worth
being around in.

00:05:46.570 --> 00:05:48.560
And so it was birth
of my twin sons

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:53.040
that motivated me to
start writing books

00:05:53.040 --> 00:06:00.140
for a broad public to explain
issues of science and issues

00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:03.850
of the world to
a public audience

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:08.790
and to try to motivate people
to take seriously the issues

00:06:08.790 --> 00:06:11.840
that the world faces,
as well as to share

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:15.910
with people the excitement that
I feel in understanding how

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:20.710
the world works, which
is basically science.

00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:25.130
And "The Third Chimpanzee"
then was the first

00:06:25.130 --> 00:06:27.720
of my books for a broad public.

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:34.830
It's about how humans became
different from other animals.

00:06:34.830 --> 00:06:39.110
The reality-- and it came
out only in the 1990s,

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:42.360
It's been known for a long
time, from the 1800s onwards,

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:45.710
that the animal species
most closely related,

00:06:45.710 --> 00:06:48.970
most similar to humans,
is chimpanzees, the two

00:06:48.970 --> 00:06:52.310
chimpanzee species of Africa,
the so-called common chimp

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:55.530
and the bonobo or pygmy chimp.

00:06:55.530 --> 00:07:00.280
But if one had asked a
biologist in the 1970s and 1980s

00:07:00.280 --> 00:07:03.580
how big is the genetic
difference between chimpanzees

00:07:03.580 --> 00:07:07.240
and humans, most of us would
have guessed, well, maybe

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:15.000
humans and chimps, maybe we
share 60%, 70% of our DNA,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.180
because we're really
very different.

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:19.280
And therefore, it
was a big surprise

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:23.960
in the 1990s when DNA
sequencing and comparison

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:28.190
techniques revealed that
humans and chimpanzees are

00:07:28.190 --> 00:07:31.930
98% identical in their DNA.

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:34.050
There's only a 2% difference.

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:38.720
So within some 2% of our
DNA is the explanation

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:45.420
for why we are sitting here
wearing clothes and talking

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:48.540
while our close
relatives the chimpanzees

00:07:48.540 --> 00:07:52.770
are in zoos, instead of
chimpanzees being here

00:07:52.770 --> 00:07:56.040
and us being in the zoos.

00:07:56.040 --> 00:08:00.580
It's also the case
that that 2% difference

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:02.940
of DNA between us
and chimpanzees

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:06.070
must explain all the
other interesting stuff.

00:08:06.070 --> 00:08:08.300
In that 2% must
be the explanation

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:12.200
for why we have language
and the chimpanzees

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:13.550
don't have language.

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:17.610
There must be the explanation
for why we have art and music

00:08:17.610 --> 00:08:19.650
and sculpture and
they don't have

00:08:19.650 --> 00:08:22.470
art and music and sculpture.

00:08:22.470 --> 00:08:24.880
There must also
be the explanation

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:29.090
for why we make war
on a large scale

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:33.690
and they don't make
war on a large scale.

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:38.010
And yet humans and chimpanzees
diverged only 6 million years

00:08:38.010 --> 00:08:38.919
ago.

00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:42.250
And until about it
80,000 years ago,

00:08:42.250 --> 00:08:45.040
humans were not a very
remarkable species.

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:46.380
Yes, we had a large brain.

00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:48.450
But we weren't doing
anything significant

00:08:48.450 --> 00:08:49.410
with that large brain.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:52.090
It's only that 70,000
years ago the first signs

00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:56.120
of art and rapid
technological innovation

00:08:56.120 --> 00:08:58.210
show up in the fossil record.

00:08:58.210 --> 00:09:00.725
What that means is
that all the things

00:09:00.725 --> 00:09:02.800
that we consider
distinctively human,

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:07.100
such as art and
music and language,

00:09:07.100 --> 00:09:09.530
they must have
developed very recently.

00:09:09.530 --> 00:09:12.510
And that means that they
must have animal precursors.

00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:17.130
We ought to be able to recognize
those animal precursors.

00:09:17.130 --> 00:09:19.550
Well, we should be
able to recognize what

00:09:19.550 --> 00:09:22.510
in chimpanzees human
art developed from.

00:09:22.510 --> 00:09:24.660
And we should be able to
recognize other animal

00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:29.350
species that have carried
art to greater lengths, much

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:32.980
greater length, than
have chimpanzees.

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:36.260
And so this first book of
mine, "The Third Chimpanzee,"

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:43.550
is about the evolution of
humans from our animal ancestors

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:47.060
and about the animal origins of
what's considered distinctively

00:09:47.060 --> 00:09:52.530
human traits, including
language, art, music, addiction

00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:55.730
to drugs, and
advanced technology.

00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:01.640
I wrote my books to
be understandable

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:04.570
to a wide public.

00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:07.520
I've always been
interested in understanding

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:09.530
things and explaining things.

00:10:09.530 --> 00:10:11.930
I have one sibling, a
younger sister, a year

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:13.610
and a half younger than I am.

00:10:13.610 --> 00:10:15.860
And so as I grew
up, I was always

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:19.940
explaining things to
my younger sister.

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:23.920
When I began in the
1980s to write articles

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:26.680
about things other than
gall bladders and birds,

00:10:26.680 --> 00:10:31.730
they were things that were
not in my area of specialty,

00:10:31.730 --> 00:10:34.470
such as the development
of language.

00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:38.480
I had to ask the
experts in these fields

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:42.790
to explain their subjects
to me and to recommend

00:10:42.790 --> 00:10:45.610
reading where I could
learn about early forms

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:46.980
of human language.

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:51.220
In short, not only had I been
explaining things to my sister,

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:54.070
but from the 1980s
onwards I was spending

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:58.130
a lot of my time trying to
explain to myself things

00:10:58.130 --> 00:11:00.540
that were not my specialty.

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:07.810
And so my books developed as
explaining to other people

00:11:07.810 --> 00:11:13.030
complex subjects in the
same way that I had learned

00:11:13.030 --> 00:11:16.090
to explain those complex
subjects to myself.

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:22.550
Initially, when I published
"Third Chimpanzee,"

00:11:22.550 --> 00:11:25.830
and then my subsequent books,
"Guns, Germs, and Steel,"

00:11:25.830 --> 00:11:28.820
about the long-term pattern
of human history, "Why

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:32.630
is Sex Fun?" about human
sexual evolution, "Collapse,"

00:11:32.630 --> 00:11:36.060
about how societies
succeed or fail

00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:39.090
at managing their
problems, most recently

00:11:39.090 --> 00:11:41.560
"The World Until
Yesterday," comparing

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:44.320
traditional tribal societies
with modern state-level

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:47.150
societies, these books
are about-- they're

00:11:47.150 --> 00:11:50.960
longish books, most of
them up to 500 pages,

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:57.170
except for "Why is Sex Fun?"
which was only 167 pages,

00:11:57.170 --> 00:12:00.970
because after 167 pages, I had
to admit I didn't understand

00:12:00.970 --> 00:12:04.580
why sex is fun in an
evolutionary sense.

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:05.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:05.130 --> 00:12:10.430
But the books are still
about complex material.

00:12:10.430 --> 00:12:15.200
And it did not occur
to me that my books

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:17.790
might get read in schools.

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:21.200
And therefore, it
surprised me in the 1990s

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:23.630
when I started giving
talks on my books

00:12:23.630 --> 00:12:27.790
to find that regularly in the
audiences for my book tours

00:12:27.790 --> 00:12:30.030
there would be school classes.

00:12:30.030 --> 00:12:33.040
And the school classes, high
school classes, middle school

00:12:33.040 --> 00:12:37.790
classes, often were the most
motivated of my listeners.

00:12:37.790 --> 00:12:39.042
They would come up afterwards.

00:12:39.042 --> 00:12:40.250
They would want books signed.

00:12:40.250 --> 00:12:41.690
They would want photographs.

00:12:41.690 --> 00:12:43.270
They would be very excited.

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:45.975
Some of them had made
t-shirts with a picture of me

00:12:45.975 --> 00:12:48.750
or with my name on the t-shirt.

00:12:48.750 --> 00:12:56.140
And so I was discovering
that school students find

00:12:56.140 --> 00:13:02.080
these big questions as
interesting as do adults.

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:04.440
Then came another
wake-up event for me,

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:08.490
which again involved my sons.

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:11.980
By the time my sons were in the
seventh grade, because they're

00:13:11.980 --> 00:13:14.380
twins, they were
at school together.

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:18.230
And one day my sons
came home from school

00:13:18.230 --> 00:13:20.400
and they were angry at me.

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:22.050
And I didn't know
what I had done

00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:25.750
to arouse their
justified wrath that day.

00:13:25.750 --> 00:13:27.430
So I asked them,
what's the matter?

00:13:27.430 --> 00:13:33.016
And they said, Daddy, your book
has been assigned to our class

00:13:33.016 --> 00:13:35.690
today.

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:37.260
And we haven't read it.

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:42.140
But we know without reading
it that it's a bad book.

00:13:42.140 --> 00:13:47.180
And worst of all, our teacher
invited you in to give a talk

00:13:47.180 --> 00:13:48.920
to our class.

00:13:48.920 --> 00:13:50.550
And you accepted.

00:13:50.550 --> 00:13:53.450
And that is so embarrassing.

00:13:53.450 --> 00:13:57.910
You are going to humiliate
us in front of our classmates

00:13:57.910 --> 00:14:02.086
by showing the stupid things
that you do and write about.

00:14:02.086 --> 00:14:05.090
Well, I'd already accepted.

00:14:05.090 --> 00:14:08.750
And so I came to my sons'
seventh grade class.

00:14:08.750 --> 00:14:13.390
My two sons were seated
in the next to back row.

00:14:13.390 --> 00:14:18.550
And I've never seen such a
portrait of utter humiliation

00:14:18.550 --> 00:14:19.730
and embarrassment.

00:14:19.730 --> 00:14:25.060
They were sitting there averted.

00:14:25.060 --> 00:14:26.760
Their faces were red.

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:28.620
They were all
scrunched up, trying

00:14:28.620 --> 00:14:31.290
to make themselves as
invisible as possible,

00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:35.240
because their father was about
to start talking and showing

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:38.880
their classmates, talking to
their classmates about things

00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:42.280
that their classmates
would utterly despise.

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:45.400
So I started talking
about my book.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:49.260
And my sons' classmates
were sitting up.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:50.425
And they were listening.

00:14:50.425 --> 00:14:52.420
And they were
beginning to smile.

00:14:52.420 --> 00:14:53.820
And they were interested.

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:56.140
And they laughed at
the appropriate places.

00:14:56.140 --> 00:14:58.150
They began asking me questions.

00:14:58.150 --> 00:15:00.150
They were really quite relaxed.

00:15:00.150 --> 00:15:03.780
It became clear to my
sons that their classmates

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:09.800
found these big questions
as interesting as do adults.

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:13.556
And gradually my sons rotated
around to face forwards.

00:15:13.556 --> 00:15:14.930
And their bodies
straightened up.

00:15:14.930 --> 00:15:18.240
And smiles came on
their face as they

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:21.845
saw that this was OK
with their classmates.

00:15:21.845 --> 00:15:24.580
And after that
lecture, my sons have

00:15:24.580 --> 00:15:29.340
become among the devoted
backers of my books.

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:32.540
If my sons hear that I
got a negative review

00:15:32.540 --> 00:15:35.320
or that someone criticized
some aspect of my book,

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:38.076
my sons immediately
become indignant.

00:15:38.076 --> 00:15:41.780
Well, that episode
then brought home to me

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:46.080
that these big questions
of science and history

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:49.800
and technology engage
not only adults,

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:54.350
but that they also
engage young people.

00:15:54.350 --> 00:15:58.790
In retrospect, that's
I think not surprising,

00:15:58.790 --> 00:16:02.310
because the subjects of my
book-- each book that I've

00:16:02.310 --> 00:16:05.170
written has been about
whatever at the time

00:16:05.170 --> 00:16:09.560
seemed to me the most
interesting unsolved problems

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:15.150
of human nature after the
previous book of mine.

00:16:15.150 --> 00:16:20.610
"Third Chimpanzee," then, about
human evolution from animals.

00:16:20.610 --> 00:16:23.380
Another big question that was
the subject of "Guns, Germs,

00:16:23.380 --> 00:16:26.090
and Steel," as I look
out at you today,

00:16:26.090 --> 00:16:29.330
it looks to me like the
great majority of you

00:16:29.330 --> 00:16:32.430
are of Old World
origin, that's to say

00:16:32.430 --> 00:16:36.690
of European or Asian
or African background.

00:16:36.690 --> 00:16:41.290
And yet if we could have been
at this spot 500 years ago,

00:16:41.290 --> 00:16:43.424
every person here
would have been

00:16:43.424 --> 00:16:47.060
of Native American origins.

00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:49.780
Why did history
turn out that way?

00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:53.520
Why was it that Europeans came
and occupied the New World?

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:58.160
Why was it not instead the case
that Native Americans expanded

00:16:58.160 --> 00:16:59.950
and occupied the Old World?

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:03.070
Or why didn't Aboriginal
Australians, why were not they,

00:17:03.070 --> 00:17:06.930
or why weren't Africans the
ones to expand over the world?

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:09.160
That really is the biggest
question of human history.

00:17:09.160 --> 00:17:13.119
But historians have not
answered that question for us.

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:16.520
And yet everybody in the
United States walking

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:20.349
around can see the
people around them.

00:17:20.349 --> 00:17:23.390
And already children
have to ask themselves,

00:17:23.390 --> 00:17:28.630
so why is it this way?

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:31.250
But historians have not
provided the answer.

00:17:31.250 --> 00:17:34.470
And in the absence of an
accepted answer to this biggest

00:17:34.470 --> 00:17:36.790
question of history,
why was it Europeans

00:17:36.790 --> 00:17:39.680
who expanded around the world,
in the absence of an accepted

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:46.030
answer, people have to come
up, at least unconsciously

00:17:46.030 --> 00:17:48.100
or without saying
it, with an answer.

00:17:48.100 --> 00:17:50.640
And everybody can see that
people look different,

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:53.440
that people have different
faces, hair color, skin

00:17:53.440 --> 00:17:54.780
color, and eye color.

00:17:54.780 --> 00:18:00.440
And therefore people assume that
inside those different faces

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:03.230
lie different brains and
the different brains are

00:18:03.230 --> 00:18:06.700
the explanation for the broad
pattern of human history,

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:11.400
although there is no evidence
whatsoever to support

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:15.130
a hypothesis of genetic
differences of intelligence

00:18:15.130 --> 00:18:16.930
between peoples of
different continents.

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:20.720
And indeed, there's evidence
in the opposite direction.

00:18:20.720 --> 00:18:24.450
So young people find these
questions interesting

00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:27.080
just as do older people.

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:43.520
Recently the first of my
books, "The Third Chimpanzee,"

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:47.680
was prepared in a version
addressed specifically

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:51.070
to young people, even though
the adult version was already

00:18:51.070 --> 00:18:54.850
being sold in schools
and read in schools.

00:18:54.850 --> 00:18:58.670
And I wondered, well, the
adult version is already

00:18:58.670 --> 00:18:59.770
being sold in schools.

00:18:59.770 --> 00:19:04.140
What does one need a
children's version for?

00:19:04.140 --> 00:19:10.470
I saw the produced young
people's version myself

00:19:10.470 --> 00:19:13.120
for the first time, the
finished version, the day

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:14.830
before yesterday.

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:19.670
And I must say it is very
user-friendly, compared

00:19:19.670 --> 00:19:25.930
to my adult books, which are
500 pages long and dense.

00:19:25.930 --> 00:19:30.800
The young people's version
contains the material

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:32.060
of the adult version.

00:19:32.060 --> 00:19:33.630
It has 16 chapters.

00:19:33.630 --> 00:19:36.560
The adult version as 19
chapter, so some of the material

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:38.330
has been compressed.

00:19:38.330 --> 00:19:42.260
And the language is
a little simpler.

00:19:42.260 --> 00:19:44.350
The sentence
structure is simpler.

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:48.000
I tend to write with a sentence
structure of the German author

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:52.350
Thomas Mann, that's to say long
sentences with many examples.

00:19:52.350 --> 00:19:56.050
My wife, who is my first
editor for all my books,

00:19:56.050 --> 00:20:00.270
my wife always says when she
sees a manuscript of my book,

00:20:00.270 --> 00:20:02.530
her first response
is always the same.

00:20:02.530 --> 00:20:05.810
Jared, why do you have
to wait until page five

00:20:05.810 --> 00:20:07.930
to say what this
chapter is about?

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:09.360
Say it on the first page.

00:20:09.360 --> 00:20:12.260
Jared, why do you have
to give 37 examples when

00:20:12.260 --> 00:20:14.320
2 examples would suffice?

00:20:14.320 --> 00:20:17.400
And so in the version of
"The Third Chimpanzee"

00:20:17.400 --> 00:20:21.370
for young people, those
of the 37 examples

00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:24.730
that survived my
wife's comments have

00:20:24.730 --> 00:20:27.830
been reduced to a
couple of examples.

00:20:27.830 --> 00:20:32.980
Technical terms are
explained more carefully.

00:20:32.980 --> 00:20:37.950
And the layout is a neater
layout than my adult books.

00:20:37.950 --> 00:20:40.930
My adult books, because
there's lots of material,

00:20:40.930 --> 00:20:44.040
the print goes towards the
top and bottom of the page

00:20:44.040 --> 00:20:46.130
and out towards the margins.

00:20:46.130 --> 00:20:50.200
But you'll see that this
young people's version has

00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:54.920
a much more inviting,
user-friendly layout.

00:20:54.920 --> 00:20:57.030
An interesting story
in this connection

00:20:57.030 --> 00:20:58.640
is that my books
have been translated

00:20:58.640 --> 00:21:00.800
into many foreign languages.

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:04.160
And as any of you who speak
a foreign language other

00:21:04.160 --> 00:21:09.260
than English know the length
of text or the length of speech

00:21:09.260 --> 00:21:11.800
that it takes to say something
in a foreign language

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:13.680
differs among languages.

00:21:13.680 --> 00:21:17.120
For example, I'm just back
from a lecture trip to Italy.

00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:20.090
And in Italian it
takes about 10%

00:21:20.090 --> 00:21:23.100
more text to say
something than in English.

00:21:23.100 --> 00:21:26.090
In German, it takes
about 30% more text

00:21:26.090 --> 00:21:28.410
to say something
than in English.

00:21:28.410 --> 00:21:32.710
And a year ago, when my book
"The World Until Yesterday"

00:21:32.710 --> 00:21:34.790
came out in a German
edition, I went to Germany

00:21:34.790 --> 00:21:36.390
to do publicity for it.

00:21:36.390 --> 00:21:38.480
And I was with my best
friends in Germany.

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:40.750
My best friend
said to me, Jared,

00:21:40.750 --> 00:21:42.540
when you write your
next book, could you

00:21:42.540 --> 00:21:47.200
please make it shorter, because
this book, 800 pages long,

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:49.340
it's so heavy that when
we lie in bed at night

00:21:49.340 --> 00:21:50.930
and would like to
be reading it, it's

00:21:50.930 --> 00:21:54.720
just too heavy to
hold and read in bed.

00:21:54.720 --> 00:22:00.490
So this young person's
version is shorter.

00:22:00.490 --> 00:22:04.156
But it's got the essence
of the adult version.

00:22:08.310 --> 00:22:13.230
Why does it make a difference
for not just adults but also

00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:17.830
young people, school
people, to understand

00:22:17.830 --> 00:22:22.760
these big questions of history
and science and of the world?

00:22:22.760 --> 00:22:25.190
Partly it's because
these big questions

00:22:25.190 --> 00:22:27.390
are as interesting
to them as to us.

00:22:27.390 --> 00:22:30.870
The other reason is
that young people

00:22:30.870 --> 00:22:32.590
are the ones who are
going to be affected

00:22:32.590 --> 00:22:36.000
by the consequences of
what we are doing now.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:37.760
Certainly I will
not be around to see

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:39.910
the end of the
tropical rainforests.

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:43.675
And many of you here
will not be around to see

00:22:43.675 --> 00:22:45.050
some of the things
that are going

00:22:45.050 --> 00:22:48.570
to happen in years like 2070.

00:22:48.570 --> 00:22:50.910
But people who are
in high school now

00:22:50.910 --> 00:22:53.050
will be seeing
what happens, will

00:22:53.050 --> 00:22:57.780
be living with the
consequences of what

00:22:57.780 --> 00:23:00.670
the world is like in 2070.

00:23:00.670 --> 00:23:04.060
So the present
school generation,

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:09.220
they're the ones who will face
the results of the decisions

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:12.770
that we're making now
based on our understanding

00:23:12.770 --> 00:23:17.380
or lack of understanding
or scorn for science.

00:23:17.380 --> 00:23:20.700
That's a strong reason
for the engagement

00:23:20.700 --> 00:23:25.890
of school people with these big
issues of science and history.

00:23:25.890 --> 00:23:30.020
Often I hear the question,
when young people get

00:23:30.020 --> 00:23:33.940
involved in these big questions
of science and history, so

00:23:33.940 --> 00:23:38.930
what can young people do to
make the world a better world?

00:23:38.930 --> 00:23:41.080
My estimate is that
the chances are

00:23:41.080 --> 00:23:44.540
about-- I would describe
myself as a cautious optimist.

00:23:44.540 --> 00:23:48.900
By that I mean that I rate
the chances as about 51%

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:54.200
that the world after 2050 will
be a world worth living in

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:58.410
with first world conditions,
and the chance at 49% that it

00:23:58.410 --> 00:24:02.220
will be irrevocably messed up.

00:24:02.220 --> 00:24:05.930
Whether we have a happy
landing or an unhappy landing

00:24:05.930 --> 00:24:09.040
depends upon our own decisions.

00:24:09.040 --> 00:24:16.030
So what can young people do
to make the right decisions,

00:24:16.030 --> 00:24:18.890
to motivate all of us to
make the right decisions?

00:24:18.890 --> 00:24:23.210
One thing that they can do is
that pretty soon or already,

00:24:23.210 --> 00:24:26.290
high school students are
going to be able to vote.

00:24:26.290 --> 00:24:29.710
So I always tell young people
when they ask what can we do,

00:24:29.710 --> 00:24:32.000
first thing I say is vote.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:36.740
The United States has
the lowest voter turnout

00:24:36.740 --> 00:24:40.550
for elections of
any major democracy.

00:24:40.550 --> 00:24:43.880
Even presidential
elections get only 60%

00:24:43.880 --> 00:24:45.600
of Americans turning out.

00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:48.460
The most recent election
for mayor of Los Angeles,

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:52.370
my city Los Angeles,
one of the largest,

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:55.680
most important cities in
the United States, only 20%

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.130
of Los Angelenos
could be bothered

00:24:58.130 --> 00:25:01.550
to vote for mayor
of their own city.

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:04.330
If government makes
bad decisions,

00:25:04.330 --> 00:25:06.610
we have only ourselves
to blame for it,

00:25:06.610 --> 00:25:10.430
for not getting engaged with
elections, for not voting.

00:25:10.430 --> 00:25:13.740
And so one thing I tell
young people is vote

00:25:13.740 --> 00:25:16.320
as soon as you're able to vote.

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:19.490
Not only vote, but also
talk to your friends

00:25:19.490 --> 00:25:22.950
and talk to other people
and encourage them to vote.

00:25:22.950 --> 00:25:26.020
And share your views with them.

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:28.650
Voting really makes a
difference in the United States.

00:25:28.650 --> 00:25:32.780
There are spectacular examples
within the last 10 years

00:25:32.780 --> 00:25:35.140
of important elections
that got decided

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:36.840
by rather narrow margins.

00:25:39.630 --> 00:25:42.970
Was it the 2000 presidential
election, in effect

00:25:42.970 --> 00:25:46.240
got decided by a margin
of several 100 votes

00:25:46.240 --> 00:25:47.570
in the state of Florida?

00:25:47.570 --> 00:25:49.460
Or conversely, you
can say it got decided

00:25:49.460 --> 00:25:52.660
by one vote on
the Supreme Court.

00:25:52.660 --> 00:25:56.850
Some years ago, the election
for governor of Washington

00:25:56.850 --> 00:26:00.470
was decided by something
like 167 votes.

00:26:00.470 --> 00:26:06.510
That means that if 17 people
who did not vote had voted

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:08.950
and each of them had
talked to and persuaded

00:26:08.950 --> 00:26:11.720
10 of their friends, that
election for governor

00:26:11.720 --> 00:26:14.590
of Washington could
have been overturned.

00:26:14.590 --> 00:26:17.270
So something that
young people can do

00:26:17.270 --> 00:26:21.630
is to vote and persuade
their friends to vote.

00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:26.030
Another thing that
people in schools can do

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:29.090
is to talk to their parents.

00:26:29.090 --> 00:26:33.230
Young people, having
learned more recently,

00:26:33.230 --> 00:26:35.780
may be more current
about important issues

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:37.530
than are their parents.

00:26:37.530 --> 00:26:41.790
Young people don't have
such rigidified minds

00:26:41.790 --> 00:26:44.300
as their parents do.

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:48.820
Talking in the business world,
I have friends in Microsoft.

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:50.270
And I have friends
in hedge funds.

00:26:50.270 --> 00:26:54.410
And so I've talked a lot of
people in the business world.

00:26:54.410 --> 00:26:58.080
There are many people
in the business world

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:00.570
who don't take environmental
issues seriously.

00:27:00.570 --> 00:27:02.780
There are also lots of
people in the business world

00:27:02.780 --> 00:27:05.970
who do take social and
environmental issues seriously.

00:27:05.970 --> 00:27:09.910
And I frequently
hear reasons why

00:27:09.910 --> 00:27:11.860
people in the
business world started

00:27:11.860 --> 00:27:14.530
to take environmental
issues seriously.

00:27:14.530 --> 00:27:18.400
It's that they
came home and there

00:27:18.400 --> 00:27:20.990
was their teenage
son or daughter.

00:27:20.990 --> 00:27:26.660
And the 14-year-old daughter
asks her CEO mother or father,

00:27:26.660 --> 00:27:30.710
Mommy or Daddy, what did you
do in your business today?

00:27:30.710 --> 00:27:34.660
And by the way, what do you
think of the climate change?

00:27:34.660 --> 00:27:38.910
And the mother or father
responds, climate change.

00:27:38.910 --> 00:27:42.430
What is that green nonsense
that you are learning in school?

00:27:42.430 --> 00:27:44.850
Climate change is the
biggest hoax ever.

00:27:44.850 --> 00:27:47.320
And I'm really disgusted that
your school is wasting time

00:27:47.320 --> 00:27:49.170
on these environmental matters.

00:27:49.170 --> 00:27:54.920
Whereupon the 14-year-old breaks
into tears, explodes in fury,

00:27:54.920 --> 00:27:59.640
says, Mommy, you are loathsome,
ignorant, and disgusting.

00:27:59.640 --> 00:28:03.540
And I'm not going to talk to
you until you educate yourself.

00:28:03.540 --> 00:28:07.880
That really gets the
attention of a parent.

00:28:07.880 --> 00:28:12.310
And I have friends in
the business world,

00:28:12.310 --> 00:28:15.070
some high-placed friends
whom I will not name,

00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:17.860
who had a transformative
experience

00:28:17.860 --> 00:28:22.260
as a result of their
teenage child telling them

00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:24.800
what they should
be learning, or had

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:29.430
a transformative experience, as
did I, as a result of starting

00:28:29.430 --> 00:28:32.850
to get concerned about the
world that their children would

00:28:32.850 --> 00:28:34.580
be launched into.

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:39.210
So in short, what can
school children do?

00:28:39.210 --> 00:28:41.660
Pretty soon they can vote.

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:43.860
They can encourage
other people to vote.

00:28:43.860 --> 00:28:45.870
They can talk to their parents.

00:28:45.870 --> 00:28:49.620
If their parents' knowledge
is 40 years out of date,

00:28:49.620 --> 00:28:52.480
as is quite likely, they
can provide their parents

00:28:52.480 --> 00:28:54.930
with more up-to-date knowledge.

00:28:54.930 --> 00:28:57.260
They have a pipeline
to their parents

00:28:57.260 --> 00:29:03.280
that their parents
employees do not have.

00:29:03.280 --> 00:29:06.530
They can really influence
the views of their parents.

00:29:06.530 --> 00:29:10.400
And then finally, there are
many things, many active things

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:15.900
that people can do
already when in schools.

00:29:15.900 --> 00:29:21.850
The day before yesterday,
while I was in Boston,

00:29:21.850 --> 00:29:25.440
someone in an audience
that I was talking to

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:28.900
explained to me that there
is a program in Boston

00:29:28.900 --> 00:29:32.090
for planting trees on
a large-scale basis.

00:29:32.090 --> 00:29:36.250
And the person being
interviewed was a 15-year-old

00:29:36.250 --> 00:29:40.880
who was involved in that
tree planting program.

00:29:40.880 --> 00:29:48.900
My own kids took part in
a march on the UCLA campus

00:29:48.900 --> 00:29:51.940
to call attention to
problems of rainforests.

00:29:51.940 --> 00:29:53.950
My kids in their
kindergarten class

00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:59.520
did that already when my
kids were six years old.

00:29:59.520 --> 00:30:02.470
Young people can
start to get involved

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:07.890
in environmental movements and
social movements, many of which

00:30:07.890 --> 00:30:13.090
have a youth organization
associated with it.

00:30:13.090 --> 00:30:17.870
And pretty soon young people
will start earning money.

00:30:17.870 --> 00:30:19.990
When they earn money
and when and if

00:30:19.990 --> 00:30:23.020
they acquire some
disposable money,

00:30:23.020 --> 00:30:26.350
they can start donating
their disposable money

00:30:26.350 --> 00:30:28.820
to causes of their choice.

00:30:28.820 --> 00:30:33.060
It may seem like
a waste of effort.

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:38.940
Why should you give $100 to
some environmental or social

00:30:38.940 --> 00:30:39.630
organization?

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:43.900
What can $100 do for
the world's problems?

00:30:43.900 --> 00:30:47.560
Well, the reality is that
effective environmental and

00:30:47.560 --> 00:30:52.320
social organizations, like World
Wildlife Fund and Conservation

00:30:52.320 --> 00:30:54.190
International and
others, they're

00:30:54.190 --> 00:30:57.100
very good at attracting
matching funds.

00:30:57.100 --> 00:31:01.020
So typically, every
$100 that ends up

00:31:01.020 --> 00:31:05.114
as a donation to World Wildlife
Fund gets parlayed into $700,

00:31:05.114 --> 00:31:09.250
seven times as much, by
attracting matching funds

00:31:09.250 --> 00:31:14.210
from governments and from
various nongovernmental

00:31:14.210 --> 00:31:15.190
organizations.

00:31:15.190 --> 00:31:20.280
So if you think that giving
$100 isn't going to do any good,

00:31:20.280 --> 00:31:23.290
think of it as giving $700.

00:31:23.290 --> 00:31:26.120
And $700 is enough to
