00:36:50.400 --> 00:36:54.550
today the Gallup
Poll released data

00:36:54.550 --> 00:36:57.400
in their long-term
consistent polling

00:36:57.400 --> 00:36:59.800
on the subject of
global warming.

00:36:59.800 --> 00:37:04.630
And they discovered that
the US population's concern

00:37:04.630 --> 00:37:07.560
for global warming
peaked in 2007.

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:10.150
It has since dropped
significantly

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:16.410
from a 40% concern in
2007 to a 34% percent

00:37:16.410 --> 00:37:19.450
of people being
concerned about it today.

00:37:19.450 --> 00:37:25.370
The interesting question would
be why are we going backwards?

00:37:25.370 --> 00:37:27.480
JARED DIAMOND: Why are
we going backwards?

00:37:27.480 --> 00:37:29.230
Good question.

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:31.100
Reasons that we
are going backwards

00:37:31.100 --> 00:37:34.960
are that we need more clear
explanations of science.

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:38.060
The great majority of
scientists don't make an effort

00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:40.540
to communicate the
results to the public.

00:37:40.540 --> 00:37:44.140
Those few, that minority
of scientists who do

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:47.270
try to explain science to
the public often get flak

00:37:47.270 --> 00:37:49.560
from other scientists
for doing so.

00:37:49.560 --> 00:37:53.270
The reaction of other
scientists to so-called science

00:37:53.270 --> 00:37:56.530
popularizers is he or she
is writing for the public

00:37:56.530 --> 00:37:58.732
because his or her
research is washed up.

00:37:58.732 --> 00:38:00.440
And there's nothing
else to do, so that's

00:38:00.440 --> 00:38:02.880
why he or she is
writing for the public.

00:38:02.880 --> 00:38:04.360
That's part of the problem.

00:38:04.360 --> 00:38:08.080
Another part of the
problem is that the science

00:38:08.080 --> 00:38:12.260
of global climate change
is really complicated.

00:38:12.260 --> 00:38:14.630
At the end of
January, I was asked

00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:19.050
to give a talk to a hedge fund
group on global climate change.

00:38:19.050 --> 00:38:22.080
And I must say, I had to
work for a couple of weeks

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:26.590
to understand the
material, elementary things

00:38:26.590 --> 00:38:29.330
such as global warming.

00:38:29.330 --> 00:38:31.965
So on the average, the world's
temperature is increasing.

00:38:31.965 --> 00:38:34.340
Wouldn't you think that that
would be good for the world,

00:38:34.340 --> 00:38:38.260
because higher temperatures
mean more crop growth,

00:38:38.260 --> 00:38:40.320
so it ought to mean more food?

00:38:40.320 --> 00:38:41.930
The reasons why
higher temperatures

00:38:41.930 --> 00:38:45.870
don't mean more food
are complicated.

00:38:45.870 --> 00:38:49.590
They include the fact that high
temperatures mean faster growth

00:38:49.590 --> 00:38:52.610
not only of wheat,
but also of weeds.

00:38:52.610 --> 00:38:55.340
And on the average,
weeds benefit more

00:38:55.340 --> 00:38:58.415
from higher temperatures than do
the crops we're interested in.

00:38:58.415 --> 00:39:01.240
In the case of wheat,
which is the major food

00:39:01.240 --> 00:39:03.640
crop of the world,
higher temperatures

00:39:03.640 --> 00:39:06.480
mean that the wheat
matures earlier,

00:39:06.480 --> 00:39:09.030
when there's less seed produced.

00:39:09.030 --> 00:39:13.920
In short, the science
involved is complicated.

00:39:13.920 --> 00:39:17.040
And scientists haven't
made the effort

00:39:17.040 --> 00:39:19.540
that they should be making
to explain the science.

00:39:19.540 --> 00:39:21.300
And then there's politics.

00:39:21.300 --> 00:39:23.680
There are people,
there are businesses

00:39:23.680 --> 00:39:26.310
that make money by
doing things that

00:39:26.310 --> 00:39:30.850
are bad for the environment,
such as the fossil fuel,

00:39:30.850 --> 00:39:33.540
such as segments of the
fossil fuel industry.

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:35.610
And when there are
things that are

00:39:35.610 --> 00:39:37.930
bad for people's
pocketbooks, that

00:39:37.930 --> 00:39:39.930
influences what they
believe to be the truth.

00:39:44.390 --> 00:39:45.950
Yes?

00:39:45.950 --> 00:39:46.840
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:46.840 --> 00:39:48.548
"The Third Chimpanzee,"
the original one,

00:39:48.548 --> 00:39:50.250
was one of my favorite books.

00:39:50.250 --> 00:39:53.050
And I already felt that
it was very accessible.

00:39:53.050 --> 00:39:55.270
Now, when I read "Guns,
Germs, and Steel,"

00:39:55.270 --> 00:39:57.520
that one was far
less accessible.

00:39:57.520 --> 00:40:00.090
But that one felt to me
like it had an underlying

00:40:00.090 --> 00:40:02.809
message of humans
aren't so different.

00:40:02.809 --> 00:40:04.600
Groups of humans are
not necessarily better

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:05.350
than other humans.

00:40:05.350 --> 00:40:06.800
That's not why,
say, Europeans are

00:40:06.800 --> 00:40:10.750
better than people from,
say, South America.

00:40:10.750 --> 00:40:14.130
What are reasons that you
chose to make a young people

00:40:14.130 --> 00:40:15.540
version of "The
Third Chimpanzee"

00:40:15.540 --> 00:40:17.289
instead of "Guns,
Germs, and Steel," which

00:40:17.289 --> 00:40:20.732
seems to have a little
bit more social relevance?

00:40:20.732 --> 00:40:21.940
JARED DIAMOND: Good question.

00:40:21.940 --> 00:40:26.364
So why did I choose to make
a young person's edition

00:40:26.364 --> 00:40:28.780
of "Third Chimpanzee" and not
of "Guns, Germs, and Steel?"

00:40:28.780 --> 00:40:31.090
The answer is, I didn't choose.

00:40:31.090 --> 00:40:35.210
Instead, it was proposed to
me by Seven Stories Press

00:40:35.210 --> 00:40:38.460
to do a young person's
edition of "Third Chimpanzee."

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:42.050
Previously a school teacher,
Boston school teacher

00:40:42.050 --> 00:40:44.730
with experience in
writing for young people,

00:40:44.730 --> 00:40:47.780
had proposed to do a young
person's edition of "Guns,

00:40:47.780 --> 00:40:51.090
Germs, and Steel," but the
rights to "Guns, Germs,

00:40:51.090 --> 00:40:53.190
and Steel" are held
by another publisher.

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:57.500
And the other publisher did
not want a children's version,

00:40:57.500 --> 00:41:00.190
because the other publisher
was concerned that a children's

00:41:00.190 --> 00:41:02.770
version would decrease
rather than increase

00:41:02.770 --> 00:41:04.890
sales of the adult version.

00:41:04.890 --> 00:41:06.490
In the case of
"Third Chimpanzee,"

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:10.100
it remains to be seen whether
the young person's edition will

00:41:10.100 --> 00:41:13.770
increase or decrease sales
of the adult version.

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:15.680
So in short, it
wasn't my choice.

00:41:15.680 --> 00:41:19.290
As for what you said about
"Guns, Germs, and Steel,"

00:41:19.290 --> 00:41:21.810
I agree with you that
"guns, Germs, and Steel"

00:41:21.810 --> 00:41:25.850
is a more complicated book
than "Third Chimpanzee,"

00:41:25.850 --> 00:41:29.230
because it's dealing with
more complicated questions,

00:41:29.230 --> 00:41:31.389
the reasons why
agriculture arose

00:41:31.389 --> 00:41:32.930
in certain parts of
the world but not

00:41:32.930 --> 00:41:34.230
in other parts of the world.

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:38.850
They don't jump into your face.

00:41:38.850 --> 00:41:40.670
So it's a more complicated book.

00:41:40.670 --> 00:41:43.510
Also, I must say in
retrospect that I

00:41:43.510 --> 00:41:49.255
think "The Third Chimpanzee"
is the most engagingly written

00:41:49.255 --> 00:41:51.020
of my books.

00:41:51.020 --> 00:41:54.866
And that's partly because
in "Guns, Germs, and Steel"

00:41:54.866 --> 00:41:57.270
and "Collapse," I had
to work really hard

00:41:57.270 --> 00:42:00.010
to explain complicated things.

00:42:00.010 --> 00:42:05.640
And the result is a
writing style more focused

00:42:05.640 --> 00:42:08.760
on clarity of explanation,
without as much

00:42:08.760 --> 00:42:13.557
of the humor and liveliness that
there is in "Third Chimpanzee."

00:42:13.557 --> 00:42:14.390
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:17.632 --> 00:42:19.033
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:42:19.033 --> 00:42:21.680
I'm a big fan of your books.
"Guns, Germs and Steel"

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:23.020
question.

00:42:23.020 --> 00:42:27.250
So I was wondering,
a lot of the reasons

00:42:27.250 --> 00:42:29.960
that there was disparity as
described in "Guns, Germs,

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:32.020
and Steel" was due
to like geography

00:42:32.020 --> 00:42:35.680
or access to different
agricultural techniques

00:42:35.680 --> 00:42:38.750
and plants, et cetera.

00:42:38.750 --> 00:42:42.120
Now that that's kind of
disappeared with technology,

00:42:42.120 --> 00:42:44.390
I still see a lot of
disparity in the world.

00:42:44.390 --> 00:42:47.850
Why isn't that going away
more quickly, in your opinion?

00:42:47.850 --> 00:42:49.670
JARED DIAMOND: Why
hasn't disparity

00:42:49.670 --> 00:42:53.770
in the world gone away when
"Guns, Germs, and Steel" is

00:42:53.770 --> 00:42:57.180
about the consequences
of an initial disparity

00:42:57.180 --> 00:42:59.410
10,000 years ago?

00:42:59.410 --> 00:43:02.560
A short answer to
your question would

00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:06.620
be that the disparity in the
origins of agriculture 10,000

00:43:06.620 --> 00:43:09.010
years ago, which
produced disparity

00:43:09.010 --> 00:43:12.890
in the origins of technology,
because the growth

00:43:12.890 --> 00:43:15.610
of technology depended upon
having enough food to feed lots

00:43:15.610 --> 00:43:18.610
of people, and surplus food
to feed people who would

00:43:18.610 --> 00:43:21.625
sit in the village and
play with dirt and fire

00:43:21.625 --> 00:43:23.550
and eventually
stumble on the idea,

00:43:23.550 --> 00:43:27.220
stumble on the discovery
of smelting copper.

00:43:27.220 --> 00:43:30.940
The differences around the world
in the origins of agriculture

00:43:30.940 --> 00:43:33.480
had to do with the
differences around the world

00:43:33.480 --> 00:43:37.820
in domesticable wild
plant and animal species.

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:41.140
The differences in wealth
around the world today

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:46.560
are partly a historical
legacy of those origins

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:48.060
of agriculture.

00:43:48.060 --> 00:43:51.390
That's to say, those places
that developed agriculture first

00:43:51.390 --> 00:43:56.090
got a head start on areas that
didn't develop agriculture,

00:43:56.090 --> 00:43:58.520
or that developed less
productive agriculture.

00:43:58.520 --> 00:44:02.200
California, for example, the
breadbasket of the United

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:04.730
States now, Native
Americans in California

00:44:04.730 --> 00:44:07.410
never developed
agriculture for themselves,

00:44:07.410 --> 00:44:08.890
even though California
is obviously

00:44:08.890 --> 00:44:10.430
a great place for agriculture.

00:44:10.430 --> 00:44:12.610
The reason is that
California is not home

00:44:12.610 --> 00:44:14.940
to domesticable wild
plant and animal species.

00:44:14.940 --> 00:44:18.600
But once agriculture developed,
first in the Fertile Crescent--

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:21.325
the area that today is
Iraq, Iran, Syria and so on.

00:44:21.325 --> 00:44:22.950
It developed there
first because that's

00:44:22.950 --> 00:44:27.320
was home to wild wheat and
barley and pigs and sheep

00:44:27.320 --> 00:44:28.360
and so on.

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:30.000
And once those
plants and animals

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.600
had been domesticated and
then spread out of the Fertile

00:44:32.600 --> 00:44:36.110
Crescent, the Fertile Crescent
then had no further advantage.

00:44:36.110 --> 00:44:38.550
Its advantage had
spread to Europe,

00:44:38.550 --> 00:44:41.270
which is much more
fertile land and richer

00:44:41.270 --> 00:44:43.150
soil than the Fertile Crescent.

00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:46.070
And so Europe rather quickly
overtook the Fertile Crescent.

00:44:46.070 --> 00:44:49.200
Reasons today why
there are differences

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:52.790
in wealth around the world,
why the world's richest

00:44:52.790 --> 00:44:55.950
country, Norway
and Luxembourg, has

00:44:55.950 --> 00:44:58.390
a per capita income
about 400 times

00:44:58.390 --> 00:45:00.880
the per capita income of the
world's poorest countries,

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:03.580
like Burundi, the
differences are partly

00:45:03.580 --> 00:45:09.820
differences in history,
history giving different head

00:45:09.820 --> 00:45:11.790
starts to different parts world.

00:45:11.790 --> 00:45:14.260
Partly it's due to
differences in geography.

00:45:14.260 --> 00:45:17.100
The Tropics are
just less productive

00:45:17.100 --> 00:45:19.830
agriculturally than the
temperate zones because

00:45:19.830 --> 00:45:24.260
of thinner, less fertile
soils and more soil pests,

00:45:24.260 --> 00:45:28.330
more disease problems
in the Tropics.

00:45:28.330 --> 00:45:31.460
There's a big role of
differences in institutions.

00:45:31.460 --> 00:45:33.810
Countries that for
one reason or another

00:45:33.810 --> 00:45:36.760
are corrupt or have
ineffective governments

00:45:36.760 --> 00:45:41.800
or don't enforce contracts or
don't obey the rule of law,

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:44.860
institutions-- I would say
institutions provide about half

00:45:44.860 --> 00:45:46.739
of the explanation.

00:45:46.739 --> 00:45:48.280
And the other half
of the explanation

00:45:48.280 --> 00:45:50.560
for the differences in wealth
around the modern world

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:52.940
are these effects of
geography and history.

00:45:52.940 --> 00:45:55.141
Does that address your question?

00:45:55.141 --> 00:45:55.766
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:45:55.766 --> 00:45:56.266
We'll see.

00:45:56.266 --> 00:45:58.790
I was also wondering
about a prediction

00:45:58.790 --> 00:46:01.840
of if it would disappear
rather quickly soon,

00:46:01.840 --> 00:46:04.232
or if it's going to
be a slower process.

00:46:04.232 --> 00:46:05.440
JARED DIAMOND: Good question.

00:46:05.440 --> 00:46:06.523
Really important question.

00:46:06.523 --> 00:46:07.690
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:07.690 --> 00:46:09.231
JARED DIAMOND: Will
those differences

00:46:09.231 --> 00:46:12.730
in wealth around
the world disappear?

00:46:12.730 --> 00:46:17.990
Well, we see that within
the last 50 years,

00:46:17.990 --> 00:46:20.430
some countries that
used to be very poor

00:46:20.430 --> 00:46:22.430
have achieved first
world standards.

00:46:22.430 --> 00:46:26.670
South Korea was desperately
poor 50 years ago.

00:46:26.670 --> 00:46:29.840
Malaysia was poor.

00:46:29.840 --> 00:46:32.960
So there are some countries
that have gotten rich quickly.

00:46:32.960 --> 00:46:37.210
China is in the process
of increasing its living

00:46:37.210 --> 00:46:38.650
standards.

00:46:38.650 --> 00:46:46.490
And so economists talk now of
a convergence economically,

00:46:46.490 --> 00:46:49.430
opposed to the divergence
in last centuries

00:46:49.430 --> 00:46:51.930
as Europe got far ahead
of the rest of the world.

00:46:51.930 --> 00:46:55.360
But there are still big
differences in wealth and power

00:46:55.360 --> 00:46:56.160
around the world.

00:46:56.160 --> 00:46:59.020
And they are important,
because poor countries,

00:46:59.020 --> 00:47:01.530
in poor countries we have
who are desperate and don't

00:47:01.530 --> 00:47:03.190
see any hope.

00:47:03.190 --> 00:47:06.610
People in those countries
will support-- they're angry.

00:47:06.610 --> 00:47:08.050
They'll support terrorists.

00:47:08.050 --> 00:47:10.850
And we're not going
to have a world

00:47:10.850 --> 00:47:13.870
worth living in 50 years from
now unless on the one hand

00:47:13.870 --> 00:47:16.680
we get control of our
environmental problems

00:47:16.680 --> 00:47:20.100
and on the other hand unless we
succeed in reducing the wealth

00:47:20.100 --> 00:47:22.020
gap between rich
and poor countries,

00:47:22.020 --> 00:47:24.840
because nowadays frustrated
people in poor countries

00:47:24.840 --> 00:47:28.135
have ways of venting their
anger, as you in New York

00:47:28.135 --> 00:47:32.867
know very well, at
people in rich countries.

00:47:32.867 --> 00:47:33.700
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:33.700 --> 00:47:35.019
JARED DIAMOND: Yeah.

00:47:35.019 --> 00:47:36.060
AUDIENCE: Yes, Professor.

00:47:36.060 --> 00:47:39.190
Thank you so much for giving
this talk, first of all.

00:47:39.190 --> 00:47:41.940
I wanted to ask on your
thoughts of over-population

00:47:41.940 --> 00:47:44.780
essentially over the
course of the next century,

00:47:44.780 --> 00:47:47.390
in regards to
whether society will

00:47:47.390 --> 00:47:50.220
be a livable place
over the next 50 years.

00:47:50.220 --> 00:47:52.460
In the 20th century
alone, the population

00:47:52.460 --> 00:47:55.430
exploded at a rate that
was unseen over the course

00:47:55.430 --> 00:47:56.610
of human history.

00:47:56.610 --> 00:47:59.219
And as other nations
continue to industrialize,

00:47:59.219 --> 00:48:00.760
it's only going to
get-- there's only

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:02.634
going to be more of us
until that trend tends

00:48:02.634 --> 00:48:03.667
to reverse itself.

00:48:03.667 --> 00:48:06.000
So I wanted to know what your
thoughts are on that role,

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:10.789
and what we can do to at least
work with that in such a way

00:48:10.789 --> 00:48:12.830
through the next-- as we
deal with climate change

00:48:12.830 --> 00:48:14.940
and as we deal with
all these other issues.

00:48:14.940 --> 00:48:16.356
JARED DIAMOND:
Very good question.

00:48:16.356 --> 00:48:19.370
So the importance of population.

00:48:19.370 --> 00:48:22.160
World population is now a
little over seven billion.

00:48:22.160 --> 00:48:26.260
The projections, if
population increases

00:48:26.260 --> 00:48:28.910
with the same first derivative
and second derivatives

00:48:28.910 --> 00:48:31.550
that it has at the
moment, the estimates

00:48:31.550 --> 00:48:33.940
are that world
population may level off

00:48:33.940 --> 00:48:36.110
at around nine billion.

00:48:36.110 --> 00:48:41.710
But that's not something with
which we should be satisfied,

00:48:41.710 --> 00:48:44.565
because we're already,
already in this world of seven

00:48:44.565 --> 00:48:47.450
billion people, there
are several billion

00:48:47.450 --> 00:48:52.090
of those seven billion
people who are starving.

00:48:52.090 --> 00:48:56.660
As countries industrialize,
the population growth rate

00:48:56.660 --> 00:48:58.500
drops dramatically.

00:48:58.500 --> 00:49:03.680
In fact, I think virtually all
first world countries today,

00:49:03.680 --> 00:49:06.480
with the possible exception
of the United States,

00:49:06.480 --> 00:49:10.390
have birth rates below
the replacement level.

00:49:10.390 --> 00:49:15.050
What's maintaining
population growth in Europe

00:49:15.050 --> 00:49:16.740
is immigration.

00:49:16.740 --> 00:49:18.710
In the United States,
population growth

00:49:18.710 --> 00:49:21.430
is partly immigration,
partly high birth rates.

00:49:21.430 --> 00:49:25.660
But in Japan, the population
has started to contract.

00:49:25.660 --> 00:49:30.680
But it's correct that
a large population

00:49:30.680 --> 00:49:32.630
is a strain on the
world's resources.

00:49:32.630 --> 00:49:35.320
What can be done about it?

00:49:35.320 --> 00:49:40.580
Here are two of the simplest
things to do about it.

00:49:40.580 --> 00:49:43.250
Examining what happens in
countries around the world,

00:49:43.250 --> 00:49:45.570
examining those countries
that have succeeded

00:49:45.570 --> 00:49:47.350
in decreasing their birth rate.

00:49:47.350 --> 00:49:50.250
One of the best predictors
of a decrease in birth rate

00:49:50.250 --> 00:49:53.580
is the empowerment of
women by enabling women

00:49:53.580 --> 00:49:55.150
to have paying jobs.

00:49:55.150 --> 00:49:56.910
For example, in Bangladesh.

00:49:56.910 --> 00:49:58.660
Bangladesh, one of
the poorer countries

00:49:58.660 --> 00:50:00.610
of the world,
Bangladesh incredibly

00:50:00.610 --> 00:50:03.790
has reduced its
population growth rate.

00:50:03.790 --> 00:50:07.660
I think it's now something like
2.3% per year, which is barely

00:50:07.660 --> 00:50:09.420
above the replacement level.

00:50:09.420 --> 00:50:11.640
The reason is that
there have been

00:50:11.640 --> 00:50:14.300
lots of jobs, so-called
sweatshop jobs,

00:50:14.300 --> 00:50:15.950
available for women
in Bangladesh.

00:50:15.950 --> 00:50:18.640
And there were protests in the
first world about the low wages

00:50:18.640 --> 00:50:19.550
that they're paid.

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:21.470
But those low wages
mean that the women

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:23.249
have the money themselves.

00:50:23.249 --> 00:50:25.290
They don't need to get
money from their husbands.

00:50:25.290 --> 00:50:27.660
And one of the first things
that Bangladesh women want

00:50:27.660 --> 00:50:30.460
to do when they have
money is to secure access

00:50:30.460 --> 00:50:31.890
to family planning.

00:50:31.890 --> 00:50:34.140
I've also seen
this in New Guinea.

00:50:34.140 --> 00:50:36.740
The New Guineans know
about family planning.

00:50:36.740 --> 00:50:39.040
But they don't have
access to means.

00:50:39.040 --> 00:50:42.700
So in answer to your
question, the first thing

00:50:42.700 --> 00:50:45.500
to do to halt
population growth rate

00:50:45.500 --> 00:50:49.450
would be to provide
economic opportunities

00:50:49.450 --> 00:50:52.150
for women in poor countries.

00:50:52.150 --> 00:50:54.680
And the other thing is
that one of the worst

00:50:54.680 --> 00:50:58.940
offenders, possibly the
worst single offender,

00:50:58.940 --> 00:51:01.500
in dealing with the
world's population problems

00:51:01.500 --> 00:51:05.670
is the United States
government and its policies.

00:51:05.670 --> 00:51:12.760
The United States is not
willing to provide foreign aid

00:51:12.760 --> 00:51:17.660
to countries tied to
family planning measures.

00:51:17.660 --> 00:51:21.800
But family planning is a
matter of sanity and survival.

00:51:21.800 --> 00:51:26.280
And it is utterly insane for
it to be a policy of the United

00:51:26.280 --> 00:51:31.840
States government to interfere
to prevent access of family

00:51:31.840 --> 00:51:34.130
planning means to
countries that want

00:51:34.130 --> 00:51:36.070
to regulate their
own population.

00:51:36.070 --> 00:51:39.155
It's not that Americans are
telling the women of Bangladesh

00:51:39.155 --> 00:51:40.600
to have fewer children.

00:51:40.600 --> 00:51:42.560
The women in Bangladesh
know perfectly well

00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:44.772
what's in their interest.

00:51:44.772 --> 00:51:46.480
My New Guinea friends
know perfectly well

00:51:46.480 --> 00:51:48.090
what's in the interest.

00:51:48.090 --> 00:51:51.860
And it is tragic for
the United States

00:51:51.860 --> 00:51:59.750
directly not to promote the
spread of family planning

00:51:59.750 --> 00:52:01.120
around the world.

00:52:01.120 --> 00:52:07.390
It's no accident that a source
of support for terrorism

00:52:07.390 --> 00:52:10.140
is Pakistan, which
is-- remember,

00:52:10.140 --> 00:52:13.920
Pakistan was a single country
until something like 1971

00:52:13.920 --> 00:52:16.380
when it broke apart into
East and West Pakistan.

00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:19.280
And we now have a
controlled experiment.

00:52:19.280 --> 00:52:22.260
In Bangladesh, family
planning was embraced.

00:52:22.260 --> 00:52:25.030
In Pakistan, family planning
has not been embraced.

00:52:25.030 --> 00:52:27.890
And the result is the
Bangladesh population growth

00:52:27.890 --> 00:52:29.830
rate near the replacement level.

00:52:29.830 --> 00:52:32.840
And in Pakistan, it's a couple
times the replacement level.

00:52:32.840 --> 00:52:33.340
Sorry.

00:52:33.340 --> 00:52:36.080
That's a long-winded, passionate
answer to your question.

00:52:36.080 --> 00:52:37.049
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:37.049 --> 00:52:37.840
JARED DIAMOND: Yes?

00:52:37.840 --> 00:52:38.460
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:38.460 --> 00:52:43.160
So you talk about the world
worth living in in 2050.

00:52:43.160 --> 00:52:45.190
And I haven't read your books.

00:52:45.190 --> 00:52:48.660
But I picked up a book
on eco-socialism once.

00:52:48.660 --> 00:52:51.890
And it presented a sort
of convincing argument

00:52:51.890 --> 00:52:55.530
that the only chance
we have at surviving

00:52:55.530 --> 00:53:00.130
is, step one, socialism,
step two, a massive planned

00:53:00.130 --> 00:53:01.780
contraction of
the world economy,

00:53:01.780 --> 00:53:04.370
and then step three,
sort of disposing

00:53:04.370 --> 00:53:08.040
industrial civilization
and no longer

00:53:08.040 --> 00:53:10.130
kind of mass producing anything.

00:53:10.130 --> 00:53:13.320
And I sort of
bought the argument.

00:53:13.320 --> 00:53:17.170
And I'm willing to give
up a lot of things.

00:53:17.170 --> 00:53:22.530
But I wouldn't be willing to
give up computers and even

00:53:22.530 --> 00:53:27.600
big data centers and stuff,
because that's how I have fun.

00:53:27.600 --> 00:53:32.620
And so to me, that wouldn't be
a world worth living in either.

00:53:32.620 --> 00:53:35.190
So I'm kind of
interested in what

00:53:35.190 --> 00:53:37.270
is the extent of
sacrifice we have

00:53:37.270 --> 00:53:40.276
to make to produce a
sustainable society?

00:53:40.276 --> 00:53:42.310
JARED DIAMOND: A big
important question.

00:53:42.310 --> 00:53:47.230
My view is
essentially your view.

00:53:47.230 --> 00:53:48.990
It's often felt--
and this may be

00:53:48.990 --> 00:53:53.890
behind the thesis of the book
that you're talking about.

00:53:53.890 --> 00:53:57.110
People often say,
there's no way that I'm

00:53:57.110 --> 00:54:01.620
going to sacrifice my
standard of living, especially

00:54:01.620 --> 00:54:05.590
for those people out
there in Somalia or Nepal.

00:54:05.590 --> 00:54:09.560
I'm not willing to give up
my computers and my access

00:54:09.560 --> 00:54:11.870
to food and my
ability to travel.

00:54:16.200 --> 00:54:18.690
But we don't have to give
up our standard of living.

00:54:18.690 --> 00:54:22.140
Something like half of
American energy consumption

00:54:22.140 --> 00:54:24.600
is wasted energy
consumption that does not

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:26.650
contribute to our
standard of living.

00:54:26.650 --> 00:54:30.420
A test of that is that the
energy consumption per person

00:54:30.420 --> 00:54:33.530
in Europe is about half
that in the United States.

00:54:33.530 --> 00:54:36.170
And yet by any reasonable
measure, the standard

00:54:36.170 --> 00:54:38.100
of living, the quality
of life in Europe

00:54:38.100 --> 00:54:41.070
is at least as high as
that in the United States.

00:54:41.070 --> 00:54:43.600
And it's because
European countries

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:47.190
do a lot that in
the United States

00:54:47.190 --> 00:54:50.840
would be decried as
socialistic, but which basically

00:54:50.840 --> 00:54:55.660
is policies aimed at the
public good and policies aimed

00:54:55.660 --> 00:54:57.890
at preventing
individuals from doing

00:54:57.890 --> 00:54:59.960
bad things to the
rest of the world.

00:54:59.960 --> 00:55:02.860
So in short, the United
States could easily

00:55:02.860 --> 00:55:07.540
reduce its energy consumption,
its consumption in general,

00:55:07.540 --> 00:55:10.250
without lowering its
standard of living, in fact,

00:55:10.250 --> 00:55:11.760
I would say increasing
its standard

00:55:11.760 --> 00:55:14.480
of living to European levels.

00:55:14.480 --> 00:55:16.167
You don't have to sacrifice.

00:55:16.167 --> 00:55:17.450
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:55:17.450 --> 00:55:18.590
JARED DIAMOND: Yes?

00:55:18.590 --> 00:55:20.960
AUDIENCE: You spoke at
the beginning about art

00:55:20.960 --> 00:55:24.512
and sculpture and music
and language being

00:55:24.512 --> 00:55:25.970
I forget how many
tens of thousands

00:55:25.970 --> 00:55:28.550
of years, less than
100,000 years old.

00:55:28.550 --> 00:55:32.170
But music and spoken
language in particular

00:55:32.170 --> 00:55:34.380
would leave no trace.

00:55:34.380 --> 00:55:37.194
What do we know about how
old they really could be?

00:55:37.194 --> 00:55:38.610
JARED DIAMOND:
Very good question.

00:55:38.610 --> 00:55:40.170
Really interesting question.

00:55:40.170 --> 00:55:40.980
What do we know?

00:55:40.980 --> 00:55:46.182
What's the evidence for how old
music and language and art are?

00:55:46.182 --> 00:55:48.140
Let's leave language to
the end, because that's

00:55:48.140 --> 00:55:49.350
the most difficult.

00:55:49.350 --> 00:55:50.150
Music.

00:55:50.150 --> 00:55:51.950
People make musical instruments.

00:55:51.950 --> 00:55:53.610
And musical
instruments have been

00:55:53.610 --> 00:55:57.360
found going back to
about 40,000 years.

00:55:57.360 --> 00:56:02.730
There are flutes carved of
bone from Paleolithic Europe.

00:56:02.730 --> 00:56:06.440
So our first evidence for
music, musical instruments,

00:56:06.440 --> 00:56:08.150
is 40,000 years ago.

00:56:08.150 --> 00:56:10.000
There could have
been, of course, music

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:12.120
that does not involve
instruments that ended up

00:56:12.120 --> 00:56:14.020
in the archaeological record.

00:56:14.020 --> 00:56:18.510
As for art, the earliest
evidence of preserved art

00:56:18.510 --> 00:56:21.250
is roughly 70,000
or 80,000 years ago.

00:56:21.250 --> 00:56:25.120
That art consists
of ostrich eggs that

00:56:25.120 --> 00:56:34.560
are perforated in Africa
and colored stones and trade

00:56:34.560 --> 00:56:41.570
in amber across Europe and
then ochre, red pigment.

00:56:41.570 --> 00:56:45.340
So the earliest evidence for
art is about 70,000 years ago.

00:56:45.340 --> 00:56:46.940
One can say, maybe
there was art,

00:56:46.940 --> 00:56:50.660
maybe there was music that did
not leave preserved remains.

00:56:50.660 --> 00:56:53.230
That's possible.

00:56:53.230 --> 00:56:55.740
As for language,
that's more difficult,

00:56:55.740 --> 00:56:59.670
because language
doesn't fossilize.

00:56:59.670 --> 00:57:02.920
There's been discussion, debate
about whether Neanderthals

00:57:02.920 --> 00:57:04.080
had language.

00:57:04.080 --> 00:57:07.850
With the sequencing of the
Neanderthal genome recently,

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:10.680
there's much interest in
the parts of the genome that

00:57:10.680 --> 00:57:13.950
are associated with language.

00:57:13.950 --> 00:57:17.440
The debate is still open
about where Neanderthals

00:57:17.440 --> 00:57:21.480
had complex language with
grammar as do modern humans.

00:57:21.480 --> 00:57:23.530
To me, the strongest
piece of evidence

00:57:23.530 --> 00:57:26.590
is that I would have
thought-- this my hypothesis--

00:57:26.590 --> 00:57:29.230
that once people get
language and can start

00:57:29.230 --> 00:57:34.500
talking and brainstorming
and storehousing information,

00:57:34.500 --> 00:57:38.320
you're going to get an explosion
of invention and technology.

00:57:38.320 --> 00:57:40.510
But the explosion of
invention and technology

00:57:40.510 --> 00:57:42.770
does not begin in the
archaeological record

00:57:42.770 --> 00:57:46.500
until within the
last 100,000 years.

00:57:46.500 --> 00:57:49.190
And so it's my guess that
complex language also

00:57:49.190 --> 00:57:51.610
emerged within the
last 100,000 years.

00:57:51.610 --> 00:57:54.890
But I would say that probably
half of archaeologists

00:57:54.890 --> 00:57:57.410
would disagree
with me about that.

00:57:57.410 --> 00:57:59.330
In short, the
origins of language

00:57:59.330 --> 00:58:01.070
and the time of the
origins of language

00:58:01.070 --> 00:58:04.660
is still a fascinating
unresolved question.

00:58:04.660 --> 00:58:05.928
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:58:05.928 --> 00:58:07.380
JARED DIAMOND: Yeah?

00:58:07.380 --> 00:58:10.140
AUDIENCE: So I was
raised with the idea

00:58:10.140 --> 00:58:13.380
that many of the institutions
that we have now in the United

00:58:13.380 --> 00:58:18.340
States and in Europe came
about or were made possible

00:58:18.340 --> 00:58:22.010
through violent revolution.

00:58:22.010 --> 00:58:24.440
Is this accurate in your view?

00:58:24.440 --> 00:58:30.160
And do you see a role,
helpful or not helpful,

00:58:30.160 --> 00:58:32.950
for violent
revolution in bringing

00:58:32.950 --> 00:58:37.740
about the change necessary
to have a livable world 100

00:58:37.740 --> 00:58:39.000
years from now?

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:40.680
JARED DIAMOND: The
reason that I began

00:58:40.680 --> 00:58:45.610
smiling as you formulated
your question was that I'm now

00:58:45.610 --> 00:58:50.070
working on a new book, for
which I was reading material

00:58:50.070 --> 00:58:51.120
this morning.

00:58:51.120 --> 00:58:53.290
And one of the questions
in the new book

00:58:53.290 --> 00:58:57.110
is about the relative
importance or frequency

00:58:57.110 --> 00:58:59.520
of violent revolution
on the one hand

00:58:59.520 --> 00:59:01.674
and peaceful evolution
on the other hand.

00:59:01.674 --> 00:59:04.090
My a new book will look at
countries around the world that

00:59:04.090 --> 00:59:06.930
underwent change, and
is asking the question

00:59:06.930 --> 00:59:09.260
about the relative importance
of violent revolution

00:59:09.260 --> 00:59:11.660
and peaceful evolution.

00:59:11.660 --> 00:59:16.220
Preliminarily I can say
there are cases of each.

00:59:16.220 --> 00:59:21.410
The United States did have
a revolution 1776 onwards.

00:59:21.410 --> 00:59:24.100
The United States also
made a major change

00:59:24.100 --> 00:59:26.960
in the 1930s, the New
Deal, that did not

00:59:26.960 --> 00:59:29.150
involve violent revolution.

00:59:29.150 --> 00:59:32.860
Britain changed greatly
from 1945 onwards,

00:59:32.860 --> 00:59:38.390
adopting a social welfare
state, dismantling its fleet.

00:59:38.390 --> 00:59:41.240
That did not involve
violent revolution.

00:59:41.240 --> 00:59:45.670
Chile changed massively in 1972.

00:59:45.670 --> 00:59:48.040
That did involve
violent revolution

00:59:48.040 --> 00:59:50.160
of a particularly horrible sort.

00:59:50.160 --> 00:59:54.420
Indonesia achieved
independence in 1948.

00:59:54.420 --> 00:59:58.260
That required, that involved
violence against the Dutch.

00:59:58.260 --> 01:00:02.210
Indonesia then had its
own revolution in 1966,

01:00:02.210 --> 01:00:05.910
when Indonesians killed about
two million other Indonesians.

01:00:05.910 --> 01:00:07.520
That was a violent revolution.

01:00:07.520 --> 01:00:11.200
Since 1966, Indonesia
has changed greatly.

01:00:11.200 --> 01:00:13.580
But there has not been
a violent revolution

01:00:13.580 --> 01:00:15.180
So a short answer
to your question

01:00:15.180 --> 01:00:19.480
is I can find examples
on both sides.

01:00:19.480 --> 01:00:22.610
And if you could ask me that
question four years from now

01:00:22.610 --> 01:00:24.210
when I've finished
my book, I'll be

01:00:24.210 --> 01:00:26.880
able to tell you whether
I discern any pattern.

01:00:26.880 --> 01:00:29.670
At the moment, I've not
yet discerned a pattern.

01:00:29.670 --> 01:00:31.110
Yes?

01:00:31.110 --> 01:00:32.600
AUDIENCE: This
question goes back

01:00:32.600 --> 01:00:35.710
to the 2% difference between
chimpanzees and humans

01:00:35.710 --> 01:00:37.960
in the genes.

01:00:37.960 --> 01:00:40.840
I'm wondering if this
is the right metric,

01:00:40.840 --> 01:00:44.490
because as an analogy,
take any large computer

01:00:44.490 --> 01:00:45.840
program that we have here.

01:00:45.840 --> 01:00:48.330
I can change very few
bits here and there

01:00:48.330 --> 01:00:50.880
to make it behave like
something completely different.

01:00:50.880 --> 01:00:53.410
And it's the same thing,
if I understand correctly,

01:00:53.410 --> 01:00:56.290
we have something
epigenetics that deals

01:00:56.290 --> 01:00:58.666
with how you control these
genes that are getting

01:00:58.666 --> 01:01:00.040
triggered on and
off so you could

01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:02.680
have the exact same
genes, but they

01:01:02.680 --> 01:01:04.100
could behave very
different people

01:01:04.100 --> 01:01:06.980
with just a few bits of
information and they changed.

01:01:06.980 --> 01:01:09.960
So the question is, then are
we looking at the right metric

01:01:09.960 --> 01:01:13.100
to say, you could have
much smaller differences

01:01:13.100 --> 01:01:15.145
in the genes itself, but
if the differences are

01:01:15.145 --> 01:01:16.520
of the right kind,
then you could

01:01:16.520 --> 01:01:19.940
have completely different
behaviors exhibited by them.

01:01:19.940 --> 01:01:23.700
So how then-- do we have
a better explanation

01:01:23.700 --> 01:01:26.760
for the differences that we see
between chimpanzees and humans

01:01:26.760 --> 01:01:29.359
other than that, well,
it's a scalar 2% number?

01:01:29.359 --> 01:01:30.650
JARED DIAMOND: You are correct.

01:01:30.650 --> 01:01:37.020
2% is a crude metric for the
overall difference in DNA.

01:01:37.020 --> 01:01:40.680
But different segments of
DNA do different things.

01:01:40.680 --> 01:01:44.500
And one might expect that
a change in the DNA that

01:01:44.500 --> 01:01:46.980
control the structure
of the voice box

01:01:46.980 --> 01:01:49.980
and the language processing
areas of the brain

01:01:49.980 --> 01:01:52.190
would have much
heavier consequences

01:01:52.190 --> 01:01:56.600
than a change in DNA for the
length of one's fingernail

01:01:56.600 --> 01:02:00.340
or for the amount of hair
on top of one's head.

01:02:00.340 --> 01:02:06.840
One of the major efforts
in molecular genetics

01:02:06.840 --> 01:02:12.190
now is in effect the approach
that you are talking about,

01:02:12.190 --> 01:02:14.880
not being satisfied with saying
that there's a 2% difference--

01:02:14.880 --> 01:02:16.820
all right, we knew
that, we learned

01:02:16.820 --> 01:02:22.610
that 20 years ago-- but trying
to find out where the 2% is

01:02:22.610 --> 01:02:24.410
and what of the
2% is significant.

01:02:24.410 --> 01:02:26.680
Lots of DNA is
thought to be junk.

01:02:26.680 --> 01:02:30.320
If 90% of DNA is junk, then
the salient differences

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:33.840
between us and chimpanzees
aren't in 2% of our DNA.

01:02:33.840 --> 01:02:36.230
They're in 0.2%
percent of our DNA.

01:02:36.230 --> 01:02:42.220
And almost every month now
or every couple months now,

01:02:42.220 --> 01:02:45.700
one sees a paper in
"Nature" or in "Science"

01:02:45.700 --> 01:02:51.230
focusing on particular areas
of human DNA or Neanderthal DNA

01:02:51.230 --> 01:02:53.160
and trying to
understand what are

01:02:53.160 --> 01:02:55.850
the differences between
human and Neanderthal DNA,

01:02:55.850 --> 01:02:58.520
or what are the differences
between human and chimpanzee

01:02:58.520 --> 01:02:59.180
DNA.

01:02:59.180 --> 01:03:00.210
So yes, you are correct.

01:03:00.210 --> 01:03:03.954
And that's a major research
program at the moment.

01:03:03.954 --> 01:03:04.861
Yeah?

01:03:04.861 --> 01:03:07.110
AUDIENCE: Regarding of violent
revolution specifically

01:03:07.110 --> 01:03:09.030
in Chile, I just finished
"Shock Doctrine."

01:03:09.030 --> 01:03:09.840
I don't know if you've read it.

01:03:09.840 --> 01:03:11.605
But it has a lot to
say about the nature

01:03:11.605 --> 01:03:13.730
of violent revolutions,
and sometimes that violence

01:03:13.730 --> 01:03:15.580
has something to do
with people coming

01:03:15.580 --> 01:03:17.690
to power that want to
have economic programs

01:03:17.690 --> 01:03:20.870
such as radical capitalism,
for example, that leaves

01:03:20.870 --> 01:03:24.740
the vast majority of people
out of wealth and prosperity

01:03:24.740 --> 01:03:27.955
and then it requires violence
in order to enforce those ideas.

01:03:27.955 --> 01:03:30.330
So I was just going to recommend
"Shock Doctrine" to you.

01:03:30.330 --> 01:03:31.270
That's all.

01:03:34.090 --> 01:03:36.080
JARED DIAMOND: Again,
an interesting question

01:03:36.080 --> 01:03:40.760
on which I'm going to reserve
judgment for several years

01:03:40.760 --> 01:03:43.110
until I've looked at
more of a database.

01:03:47.621 --> 01:03:48.120
Yes?

01:03:48.120 --> 01:03:50.040
AUDIENCE: Can I cheat
and get a second one?

01:03:50.040 --> 01:03:53.052
This is data again.

01:03:53.052 --> 01:03:55.694
And I'd like to speak
against the need

01:03:55.694 --> 01:03:56.652
for violent revolution.

01:03:59.820 --> 01:04:01.980
This year in New York
City the winter air

01:04:01.980 --> 01:04:05.090
is cleaner than it
has been in 50 years.

01:04:05.090 --> 01:04:07.120
50 years.

01:04:07.120 --> 01:04:10.030
It turns out that it only took
three years, the last three

01:04:10.030 --> 01:04:13.610
years, to get it to that point.

01:04:13.610 --> 01:04:16.310
What happened was
that it was discovered

01:04:16.310 --> 01:04:18.200
that 1% of the
buildings in the city

01:04:18.200 --> 01:04:20.230
were producing as much
pollution as all the cars

01:04:20.230 --> 01:04:22.390
and trucks in the entire city.

01:04:22.390 --> 01:04:24.890
Yet, every one of
those buildings

01:04:24.890 --> 01:04:28.114
could actually save money
by using cleaner methods.

01:04:28.114 --> 01:04:30.530
So what we did was we went to
those buildings and we said,

01:04:30.530 --> 01:04:30.730
look.

01:04:30.730 --> 01:04:32.380
You can save money
by being cleaner.

01:04:32.380 --> 01:04:33.730
And we got the law changed.

01:04:33.730 --> 01:04:34.830
It was easy to get
the law changed,

01:04:34.830 --> 01:04:37.371
because once you could tell the
mayor, Bloomberg at the time,

01:04:37.371 --> 01:04:41.240
and the City Council that you're
forcing people to save money,

01:04:41.240 --> 01:04:42.440
they changed the law.

01:04:42.440 --> 01:04:44.570
And now it's illegal in
New York City-- well,

01:04:44.570 --> 01:04:46.790
there are a couple
buildings until 2015

01:04:46.790 --> 01:04:50.950
can do it-- to burn what's
called number six fuel oil.

01:04:50.950 --> 01:04:54.690
The air is cleaner today
than it's been in '50 years.

01:04:54.690 --> 01:04:55.630
Totally quiet.

01:04:55.630 --> 01:04:56.960
Nobody knows about it.

01:04:56.960 --> 01:04:58.580
Didn't even raise a noise.

01:04:58.580 --> 01:05:01.040
There was no violence involved.

01:05:01.040 --> 01:05:03.100
But we've accomplished
big things.

01:05:03.100 --> 01:05:05.237
If one goes through
the problems we have,

01:05:05.237 --> 01:05:06.320
yeah, you do have choices.

01:05:06.320 --> 01:05:08.080
You can have violent revolution.

01:05:08.080 --> 01:05:09.569
But the other
approach, and I think

01:05:09.569 --> 01:05:11.360
you'll discover this
if you look carefully,

01:05:11.360 --> 01:05:15.330
is that most of the problems we
have have profitable solutions.

01:05:15.330 --> 01:05:18.400
What we have to do is we have
to have the courage, the balls,

01:05:18.400 --> 01:05:20.140
and the persistence
to go out and find

01:05:20.140 --> 01:05:24.680
the profitable solutions
and to encourage

01:05:24.680 --> 01:05:27.080
people to do those things.

01:05:27.080 --> 01:05:29.570
To a great extent, we
don't need sacrifice

01:05:29.570 --> 01:05:30.660
to solve these problems.

01:05:30.660 --> 01:05:33.620
What we need is we need
wisdom and we need courage.

01:05:33.620 --> 01:05:36.340
JARED DIAMOND: That's a
very good way to put it.

01:05:36.340 --> 01:05:38.630
I like your term
profitable solutions.

01:05:38.630 --> 01:05:41.420
And I'll give you
an example of it.

01:05:41.420 --> 01:05:43.860
On the board of
Conservation International,

01:05:43.860 --> 01:05:46.310
the international
environmental organization

01:05:46.310 --> 01:05:48.950
that I'm involved
with, on the board

01:05:48.950 --> 01:05:52.660
is the son of the
founder of Walmart.

01:05:52.660 --> 01:05:56.250
So profitable
solutions for Walmart.

01:05:56.250 --> 01:06:01.040
Walmart 10 years ago
was not at all concerned

01:06:01.040 --> 01:06:02.940
about environmental matters.

01:06:02.940 --> 01:06:06.435
And then Walmart woke up
a really elementary fact,

01:06:06.435 --> 01:06:09.690
namely that Walmart has
the largest private fleet

01:06:09.690 --> 01:06:11.400
of trucks in the United States.

01:06:11.400 --> 01:06:14.300
I think it's second only to the
US government fleet of trucks.

01:06:14.300 --> 01:06:16.640
And the fuel efficiency
of Walmart trucks

01:06:16.640 --> 01:06:20.070
was rather bad, six
miles per gallon.

01:06:20.070 --> 01:06:22.100
Walmart was not
getting any benefit

01:06:22.100 --> 01:06:25.010
from having these lousy
fuel-burning trucks.

01:06:25.010 --> 01:06:27.380
In fact, they were wasting
a lot of money on it.

01:06:27.380 --> 01:06:30.000
And so Walmart
embarked on a program

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:32.940
to increase the fuel
efficiency of its trucks

01:06:32.940 --> 01:06:37.060
to 18 miles per gallon, which
means a profitable solution,

01:06:37.060 --> 01:06:41.640
saving 2/3 of their
expenditure for truck fuel.

01:06:41.640 --> 01:06:44.340
Some of the solutions
were simple.

01:06:44.340 --> 01:06:46.490
Truckers, truck drivers
have to pull over

01:06:46.490 --> 01:06:49.120
every 10 hours or so by law.

01:06:49.120 --> 01:06:51.120
And if they're not
near a motel, they

01:06:51.120 --> 01:06:53.680
pull over in the truck
by the side of the road.

01:06:53.680 --> 01:06:55.550
And if it's hot out
or if it's cold out,

01:06:55.550 --> 01:06:57.940
they turn on the heater
or the air conditioner.

01:06:57.940 --> 01:07:02.810
Well, until relatively
recently, Walmart trucks

01:07:02.810 --> 01:07:05.120
in the cabin, heated
or air conditioned

01:07:05.120 --> 01:07:09.520
by leaving the motor
of the truck running.

01:07:09.520 --> 01:07:12.600
Walmart got the
elementary idea, we

01:07:12.600 --> 01:07:15.130
can put a space heater or
a space air conditioner

01:07:15.130 --> 01:07:17.700
in the cabin and not keep
running the motor just

01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:21.770
in order to keep the
cabin warm or cold.

01:07:21.770 --> 01:07:24.060
And then Walmart
has been working

01:07:24.060 --> 01:07:28.760
on developing hybrid trucks,
so these are like Priuses,

01:07:28.760 --> 01:07:32.030
but they're gigantic,
these 18-wheeler Priuses,

01:07:32.030 --> 01:07:33.050
hybrid trucks.

01:07:33.050 --> 01:07:36.950
Walmart has also been--
it has some trucks

01:07:36.950 --> 01:07:41.180
running on biofuels, namely the
chicken drippings that come off

01:07:41.180 --> 01:07:45.650
of fried chicken in supermarkets
and department stores.

01:07:45.650 --> 01:07:48.600
Those drippings get
converted into fuel.

01:07:48.600 --> 01:07:50.610
And so Walmart
has biofuel trucks

01:07:50.610 --> 01:07:56.160
running on in effect
processed chicken drippings.

01:07:56.160 --> 01:07:59.355
What this boils down to
is this is another example

01:07:59.355 --> 01:08:01.580
of profitable solutions.

01:08:01.580 --> 01:08:05.190
Walmart is reducing
fossil fuel consumption.

01:08:05.190 --> 01:08:07.380
But they're saving
money in the process.

01:08:07.380 --> 01:08:10.895
And one of the reasons why I'm
cautiously optimistic, rather

01:08:10.895 --> 01:08:13.360
than pessimistic, one of
the reasons why I'm not

01:08:13.360 --> 01:08:15.080
going to tell you
let's all go outside

01:08:15.080 --> 01:08:19.220
and commit a mass suicide, a
reason for my cautious optimism

01:08:19.220 --> 01:08:22.240
is that within the last
decade lots of increasing

01:08:22.240 --> 01:08:25.069
numbers of big companies
have discovered, as you say,

01:08:25.069 --> 01:08:25.940
possible solutions.

01:08:25.940 --> 01:08:27.029
I like your term.

01:08:27.029 --> 01:08:28.710
Perhaps that's a
good upbeat note

01:08:28.710 --> 01:08:32.040
on which to end the formal
part of the discussion.

01:08:32.040 --> 01:08:33.419
Any of you want
books signed, I'm

01:08:33.419 --> 01:08:34.710
happy to sign books afterwards.

01:08:34.710 --> 01:08:44.768
[APPLAUSE]

